    "Original Requirements": "Hospital Triage Queue System\n\nA system for emergency room intake that prioritizes patients based on\nclinical urgency. It ensures critical cases are surfaced to medical\nstaff immediately and that the waiting queue always reflects current\npatient conditions in a high-pressure environment.\n\nCore features:\n- Register incoming patients with their name and presenting symptoms\n- Assign each patient an urgency level from 1 (critical) to 5 (non-urgent) based on the symptoms\n- Order the queue by urgency level first, then by arrival time within the same level\n- Reorder the queue immediately whenever a new patient arrives or an existing patient is re-triaged to a different urgency level\n- Let a physician take the patient at the head of the queue, removing them from the queue\n- Show a live dashboard of the queue with each patient's urgency and waiting time",
    "Project Name": "hospital_triage_queue",
    "Product Goals": [
        "Ensure clinical urgency is the primary driver of queue order",
        "Provide real-time queue updates to support fast-paced decision making",
        "Deliver a clear, intuitive dashboard for medical staff at a glance"
    ],
    "User Stories": [
        "As a triage nurse, I want to quickly register a patient with their name and symptoms so that they enter the queue with an appropriate urgency level.",
        "As a physician, I want to see the queue sorted by urgency and waiting time so that I can attend to the most critical patient first.",
        "As a charge nurse, I want the queue to reorder automatically when a patient's condition changes so that the list always reflects current priorities.",
        "As a physician, I want to take the next patient from the head of the queue with one click so that I can start treatment immediately.",
        "As an ER manager, I want a live dashboard showing each patient's urgency and waiting time so that I can monitor flow and identify bottlenecks."
    ],
    "Competitive Analysis": [
        "Epic Triage Module: Integrated with EHR, but complex setup and not real-time focused.",
        "Cerner Triage: Strong clinical decision support, but queue visualization is basic.",
        "Meditech Triage: Reliable but outdated UI and slow updates.",
        "Q-Flow: General queue management, not tailored for clinical urgency.",
        "LobbyTracker: Good for patient check-in, lacks medical triage logic.",
        "PatientTrak: Real-time tracking, but no built-in urgency-based sorting.",
        "WaitTime: Focuses on estimated wait times, not dynamic re-prioritization."
    ],
    "Competitive Quadrant Chart": "quadrantChart\n    title \"Reach and Engagement of Triage Systems\"\n    x-axis \"Low Reach\" --> \"High Reach\"\n    y-axis \"Low Engagement\" --> \"High Engagement\"\n    quadrant-1 \"We should expand\"\n    quadrant-2 \"Need to promote\"\n    quadrant-3 \"Re-evaluate\"\n    quadrant-4 \"May be improved\"\n    \"Epic Triage\": [0.7, 0.4]\n    \"Cerner Triage\": [0.6, 0.5]\n    \"Meditech Triage\": [0.5, 0.3]\n    \"Q-Flow\": [0.4, 0.6]\n    \"LobbyTracker\": [0.3, 0.7]\n    \"PatientTrak\": [0.5, 0.8]\n    \"WaitTime\": [0.2, 0.5]\n    \"Our Target Product\": [0.6, 0.8]",
    "Requirement Analysis": "The system must handle high-pressure ER environments where patient conditions change rapidly. The core algorithm is a priority queue sorted first by urgency level (1 highest) and then by arrival time (FIFO within same urgency). Every patient registration or re-triage triggers an immediate reorder. The physician action removes the head patient. The dashboard must update in real-time (e.g., via WebSocket or polling) to show current queue, urgency, and waiting time. The system should be simple to use with minimal clicks. No authentication or multi-user roles are specified, but they may be needed in practice. Data persistence is assumed for audit and continuity.",
