{
    "Implementation approach": "We will build the Hospital Triage Queue System as a web application using FastAPI (async Python web framework) for the backend, SQLite with SQLAlchemy for lightweight persistence, and a simple HTML/CSS/JavaScript frontend that polls the REST API every 500ms to simulate real-time updates. For concurrency, we will use an asyncio lock (asyncio.Lock) to protect queue mutations. The symptom-to-urgency mapping will be implemented as a configurable rule engine based on the ESI (Emergency Severity Index) standard, with a default mapping of common symptoms to urgency levels. The system will support patient registration, automatic urgency assignment, manual re-triage, physician dequeue, and a live dashboard showing colored urgency badges and auto-updating waiting times.",
    "File list": [
        "main.py",
        "models.py",
        "queue_manager.py",
        "triage_rules.py",
        "dashboard.py",
        "requirements.txt",
        "static/index.html",
        "static/style.css",
        "static/script.js"
    ],
    "Data structures and interfaces": "\nclassDiagram\n    class Patient {\n        -int id\n        -str name\n        -str symptoms\n        -int urgency  # 1 (critical) to 5 (non-urgent)\n        -datetime triage_time\n        -datetime arrival_time\n        -int waiting_seconds  # computed\n        +__init__(id, name, symptoms, urgency, triage_time, arrival_time)\n        +to_dict() dict\n    }\n    class TriageRuleEngine {\n        -dict symptom_urgency_map  # e.g., {'chest pain': 1, 'fever': 3}\n        -list default_rules\n        +__init__(rule_file: str)\n        +assign_urgency(symptoms: str) int\n        +load_rules()\n    }\n    class QueueManager {\n        -list _queue  # sorted list of Patient objects\n        -int _next_id\n        -Lock _lock\n        -Database db  # SQLite connection\n        +__init__(db)\n        +add_patient(name: str, symptoms: str, manual_urgency: Optional[int]) Patient\n        +dequeue() Patient\n        +re_triage(patient_id: int, new_urgency: int) Patient\n        +get_queue() list[dict]\n        +get_patient(patient_id: int) Patient\n        +_sort_queue()\n        +save_state()\n        +load_state()\n    }\n    class Database {\n        -sqlite3.Connection conn\n        +__init__(db_path: str)\n        +create_tables()\n        +insert_patient(patient: Patient)\n        +update_patient(patient: Patient)\n        +delete_patient(patient_id: int)\n        +fetch_all() list\n        +close()\n    }\n    class DashboardAPI {\n        -QueueManager queue\n        +__init__(queue)\n        +get_queue_data() dict  # includes computed waiting times\n        +get_stats() dict\n    }\n    class FastAPIApp {\n        -TriageRuleEngine rule_engine\n        -QueueManager queue_manager\n        -DashboardAPI dashboard\n        +start()\n        +register_routes()\n        +on_event('startup')\n        +on_event('shutdown')\n        -async def post_register(patient_data) dict\n        -async def post_dequeue() dict\n        -async def post_re_triage(patient_id, new_urgency) dict\n        -async def get_queue() dict\n    }\n    FastAPIApp --> TriageRuleEngine\n    FastAPIApp --> QueueManager\n    FastAPIApp --> DashboardAPI\n    QueueManager --> Database\n    QueueManager --> Patient\n    TriageRuleEngine --> Patient : assigns urgency\n    DashboardAPI --> QueueManager\n",
    "Program call flow": "\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant Nurse as Nurse (Browser)\n    participant UI as Frontend (static/script.js)\n    participant API as FastAPI Backend (main.py)\n    participant QM as QueueManager\n    participant DB as Database (SQLite)\n    participant RE as TriageRuleEngine\n\n    Note over Nurse,UI: Registration\n    Nurse->>UI: Fill form (name, symptoms, optional urgency)\n    UI->>API: POST /register (name, symptoms, manual_urgency)\n    API->>QM: add_patient(name, symptoms, manual_urgency)\n    QM->>RE: assign_urgency(symptoms)\n    RE-->>QM: urgency (int)\n    QM->>DB: insert_patient(new_patient)\n    DB-->>QM: success\n    QM->>QM: _sort_queue()\n    QM-->>API: return patient dict\n    API-->>UI: JSON with patient data\n    UI->>UI: update dashboard\n\n    Note over Physician,UI: Dequeue\n    Physician->>UI: Click \"Take\" on top patient\n    UI->>API: POST /dequeue\n    API->>QM: dequeue()\n    QM->>QM: acquire lock\n    QM->>DB: delete_patient(top_patient.id)\n    DB-->>QM: success\n    QM->>QM: remove from internal queue\n    QM->>QM: release lock\n    QM-->>API: return removed patient\n    API-->>UI: JSON with removed patient\n    UI->>UI: update dashboard\n\n    Note over Nurse,UI: Re-triage\n    Nurse/Physician->>UI: Select new urgency from dropdown\n    UI->>API: POST /re_triage (patient_id, new_urgency)\n    API->>QM: re_triage(patient_id, new_urgency)\n    QM->>QM: acquire lock\n    QM->>DB: update_patient(updated_patient)\n    DB-->>QM: success\n    QM->>QM: update urgency and triage_time\n    QM->>QM: _sort_queue()\n    QM->>QM: release lock\n    QM-->>API: return updated patient dict\n    API-->>UI: JSON\n    UI->>UI: update dashboard\n\n    Note over UI,API: Dashboard Polling\n    UI->>API: GET /queue (every 500ms)\n    API->>QM: get_queue()\n    QM->>QM: compute waiting times (current_time - arrival_time)\n    QM-->>API: list of patient dicts\n    API-->>UI: JSON\n    UI->>UI: render table with urgency badges and waiting times\n",
    "Anything UNCLEAR": "The symptom-to-urgency mapping algorithm requires a clinical basis. We will implement a default rule set based on common ESI indicators (e.g., chest pain -> 1, severe abdominal pain -> 2, minor laceration -> 4) and make the rules configurable via a JSON file. Multi-user concurrency is handled via an asyncio lock on the QueueManager, but in a distributed deployment a database-level lock or optimistic concurrency would be needed. For this prototype, single-instance is assumed."
}
[/CONTENT]
